I think a lot about the millennials, who were the last generation able to build connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during the golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
one could dive directly into things without having to worry about the source, since it was not so easy to determine.
without having any reason to question the pedestal on which we placed them, parasocial relationships had become the foundations of our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on, my friends and I would order pizzas and watch the series every Thursday.
It was like nothing we have now with streaming, where 12 episodes are available all at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified private spaces.
unconsciously, we long to reconnect with the universal community that surrounded all of this
That's why so many of us watch obsessively series like The Office or movies like Présentateur vedette, which are full of short references, like memes.
we would repeat these references, knowing that most people knew them
now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
There's too much to see and no way to rationalize it all... will we escape the oversaturation?
We get caught in cycles of discovering new media, only to end up realizing that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while acknowledging that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
We enter parasocial relationships by paying more attention.
We understand that it is difficult to reach positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
Due to a lack of collective awareness about media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
Some of us continue to place people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall from it.
We are in a turbulent period, and I can't wait to see where it takes us.
Inclusion and safety should be the norm.
